{{.B}}{{.U}}NAME{{.R}}
	mksvc - a hardened, opinionated systemd service generator

{{.B}}{{.U}}SYNOPSIS{{.R}}
	mksvc <name> <path> [options]

{{.B}}{{.U}}DESCRIPTION{{.R}}
	mksvc creates production-ready systemd environments with a focus on
	security and minimal manual intervention. It generates service units,
	sysusers and logrotate configs with smart dependency ordering.

{{.B}}{{.U}}OPTIONS{{.R}}
	{{.B}}-h, --help{{.R}}
		Show this detailed manual page.

	{{.B}}-v, --version{{.R}}
		Print version information and exit.

	{{.B}}-i, --interactive{{.R}}
		Configure service capabilities manually via prompts.

{{.B}}{{.U}}CONFIGURATION{{.R}}

	{{.B}}Network Access{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}enabled{{.R}})
		Controls AF_INET/AF_INET6 address families and creates a private
		loopback-only namespace when disabled. Disabling this effectively
		"airgaps" the service, preventing all external communication.
		Disable for local processing tools, offline bots or crons.

	{{.B}}Server Mode / Listening{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}enabled{{.R}})
		Controls port binding and startup ordering. When enabled, it allows
		the service to bind to TCP/UDP ports (disables 'SocketBindDeny')
		and ensures 'network-online.target' is reached before starting.
		Required for web servers, databases and APIs.

	{{.B}}Privileged Ports (<1024){{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}disabled{{.R}})
		Allows binding to ports below 1024 (e.g., 80/443) by granting the
		CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE capability to the service. Keep disabled if
		you can bind to high ports (>=1024) and use a reverse proxy
		(nginx) or port forwarding.

	{{.B}}JIT/Executable Memory{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}disabled{{.R}})
		Controls 'MemoryDenyWriteExecute'. Standard Go binaries do not need
		this. Enable only for:
		 - Runtimes with JIT (Java, Node.js, PHP)
		 - Go libraries using WASM (e.g., wazero)
		 - Applications using Go plugins (.so) or C-FFI

	{{.B}}Writable Working Directory{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}disabled{{.R}})
		If disabled, the service root is mounted read-only via 'ReadOnlyPaths'.
		This prevents compromised services from modifying their own binaries
		or configs. Enable only if the app persists local data (e.g., SQLite).
		{{.B}}Note:{{.R}} Logs usually do not require this (see below).

	{{.B}}Runtime Directory / IPC{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}disabled{{.R}})
		Creates /run/<name> (tmpfs) owned by the service. Use this for
		Unix domain sockets (.sock) or PID files to avoid polluting global
		directories. Cleaned up automatically on stop.

	{{.B}}Hardware Devices{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}disabled{{.R}})
		Grants access to hardware (USB, serial, GPU) and adds the user to
		'dialout/plugdev'. Enable only if the service directly interacts
		with physical hardware attached to the host.

	{{.B}}Subprocesses{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}disabled{{.R}})
		Restricts the filesystem view by masking /bin, /usr/bin, etc.
		This significantly reduces attack surface. Enable only if your
		app shells out to external commands (e.g., ffmpeg, git).

	{{.B}}Separate Logs Directory{{.R}} (Default: {{.B}}enabled{{.R}})
		Organizes logs into <path>/logs/ instead of the root. This keeps
		the working directory clean. Systemd handles the writes, so this
		works even if 'Writable Working Directory' is disabled.

